You can be fully knowledgeable about a diagnosis due to INTENSE and overly obsessive study and there’s still someone who will stigmatize that diagnosis and invalidate your journey. In all reality? Seeing a fit for yourself in a diagnosis and using coping mechanisms that actually help you coinciding with that diagnosis is never a negative thing. The only negative is that you may be outside of someone else’s box of what they think they understand about that condition. Don’t let that deter you from your self journey. I'm just going to put all my information out here so I dont have to repeat myself in the comments !  - Suzie is my service dog (she is technically in training but that gives her the same legal protection) . I am self training and getting certification through the help of a non profiit program in York PA called 4 Paws 4 a cause. We have been training since August 2023 and are almost finished!  - Some of her tasks are deep pressure, mobility assistance, gaurding, sensing my health conditions flairing, medica appointment companionship, and more (that I dont want or need to disclose)  - I am disabled, I have physical and psychological impairments that make daily life difficult. Without my service dog I would have a lower quality of life.   * if you see a service dog video on the internet please dont ask what the dog does for the person in the comments  *if you work somewhere and as the employee you question the legitamacy of a service dog please see below _____ This is pulled right from the ADA.gov site  "When it is not obvious what service an animal provides, only limited inquiries are allowed. Staff may ask two questions: (1) is the dog a service animal required because of a disability, and (2) what work or task has the dog been trained to perform. Staff cannot ask about the person’s disability, require medical documentation, require a special identification card or training documentation for the dog, or ask that the dog demonstrate its ability to perform the work or task."  #dogs #servicedog #disabled #disability #servicedogtraining #dog #workingdog  #psychiatricservicedog #poodle #doodle #disabilityaid #puppy #educate #advocate #autisticAdult #disabilityadvocate #autistic #heds #geneticdisorder #chronicillness #audhd #servicedogsoftiktok

The are traits of autism that are often beneficial for individuals who have them. Like with all traits of autism. The majority of these things are things that happen to everyone sometimes, but tend to happen more often or more intensely for autistic people. For some of these traits there may be ways they would be the opposite of beneficial at times as well.  I am not trying to say that autism is all sunshine and rainbows, it's not. But like most things there positives and negatives so it important to draw attention to both.  #autistic #autism #autismacceptance #autismawareness #autisticadult #autistictiktok #autisticcreator #autisticadvocate #autisticpride #autisticandproud

Sometimes, I don’t make my bed. I skip the gym. The laundry sits there for days (okay, sometimes longer 🙃), and work? It’s not always my best. And you know what? That’s okay. Life in 2024 feels like a rollercoaster for all of us, especially as a neurodivergent person. There are peaks when I’m on top of everything, and valleys where even getting out of bed feels like an accomplishment. The truth is, it’s normal. We’re human. Life is messy, especially when you're navigating mental health, neurodivergence, or just being alive right now. It’s not about being “perfect” or having it all together—because, honestly, who does? ✨ So, here's your reminder: if you're not “crushing it” today (or this week, or this month), you’re still doing enough. You’re still worthy. Let’s normalize the valleys as much as we celebrate the peaks. ⛰️ 💕 #neurodivergent #selfcare #aba #behaviorexplained #fyp #autism #neurodiversity #autisticadult #audhd #adhd #autismsupport #mentalhealthmatters #breakingthestigma #2024

CONTEXT IS EVERYTHING 👇 yes, as a worker I do post good looking things of myself, but my page provides so much depth & context. my content, as individual pieces, are obviously a small part of a whole & I am transparent w/ my disabilities. This creator wouldn't have gotten under my skin so much if they hadn't infantilized autistic women & failed in providing any disability or SA information. Also, I'm allowed to romanticize my own disabilities for the sake of coping & helping other disabled people cope, but it's not okay for someone on the outside to romanticize autism for the sake of views. Some may see this as "more representation" or "normalizing autism" but I just see a man talking about infantalizing women w/ a disability bc he obviously doesn't care enough to provide the nuance our vulnerable community needs. There's a way to say what he wanted to say respectfully & this wasn't it. The bio in this person's profile is "unapologetic & authentic" which leads me to believe that he genuinely won't care about any constructive criticism & will only pay attention to the autistic women in the comment section who finally feel seen. (Did I mention we're a vulnerable community? This wasn't easy for me to talk about but it's something that needs to be talked about. Medical gaslighting is a serious issue.... people are dying out there. I bet u most of my loved ones that passed away probably would still be here if doctors just listened to them sooner. My grandma was terrified to go to hospitals and see doctors cuz she was constantly getting gaslighted by doctors.  I didn't understand why until I got older and had to start advocating for myself.  This is unacceptable behavior that doctors should not be getting away with.  It's not right! And my heart breaks for all the people who been gaslighted and neglected by medical professionals.  I have every right to be worried about my own health as I have been and am currently going through medical neglect and gaslighting. This is why I have severe medical trauma. When I'm having severe symptoms I just try to push through it cuz I know going to a hospital will do me no good.  I been turned away when asking for help all because I'm a woman whose disabled and poor. Women, plus sized people, LGBTQ plus, POC, disabled, and low income people experience this type of medical abuse way more than white cis men. That doesn't mean it doesn't happen to white cis men or rich people. Just the majority of those people I listed have to deal with this even more.  DOCTORS please have compassion and listen to your patients and try to help us. To the doctors who are doing this field for the right reasons, thank u.  This needs to change tho. With the tachymon app no longer supported by my watch, I decided it couldn’t hurt to do several lean tests before my cardiology appointment just to know and have it on hand. My partner ran the test with me. I’m not looking for advice, just sharing. I’ve learned that reddit is a fairly judgmental and unsafe space (just by reading comments) and didn’t realize there was so much gatekeeping there about POTS and dysautonomia. Tiktok has been such a safe space. Anyways today was a high symptom day and I took a beta blocker. I’ll do this several more times but in a way I was surprised to see my heart rate stay high for that long. And it was brutal by the end. VD: picture of the 10 minute lean test results showing start bpm 65, end bpm 103. Navigating a simple conversation can feel like a mental marathon for many autistic adults with less visible support needs. Behind every smile and nod is a complex process of decoding social cues and managing expressions. It’s an invisible effort that often goes unnoticed, yet it's a significant part of our daily lives. It’s absolutely exhausting and can lead to meltdowns after prolonged masking.  By sharing this, I hope to shed light on the unseen struggles and foster a deeper understanding of autism. Can you relate to this? How have you started the process of unmasking? I was diagnosed two years ago and still don’t feel comfortable letting my guard down.  [Text ID: Thoughts during conversations as an autistic adult.]  [ID: A video of Syanne, a multiracial disabled Latina, looking into the camera as if the camera was another person. Replying to @mangledunicorn425 There is a place for self-diagnosed people in research. However, the information gathered from this form will be used to fund research that only includes formally diagnosed autistic people, because what they are looking for requires identifiable links between co-occurring conditions and autism, and their goal is largely prevention and treatment of those co-occurring conditions and the impact they have on autistic traits throughout the lifespan. Formally diagnosed people, who have already submitted a large amount of genetic information to these entities performing the research, will provide a large enough and accurate enough database to conduct research that will benefit ALL OF US. Nobody is leaving you out, they are simply giving the IACC what they are looking for. #fyp #autisticadult #autism #neurodivergent

What is a “spiky” neurodivergent spectrum trait profile? It means that a person can experience their specific neurodivergent traits unevenly and they can also change over time. Acceptance and inclusion should not require special labeling except in unique circumstances. Trick-or-treating is an opportunity for inclusion and acceptance. We can teach and model acceptance and inclusion without needing special buckets, signs, badges, shirts, harm bands, etc. In case someone brings up wandering as a behavior of concern, precautions can certainly be taken for safety, but a wandering child is just as likely to put down a blue bucket as they are to keep it with them. Other precisions are fare more effective and do not result in singling out or tokenization. We are people. We do NOT want to be your inspiration. We do NOT want your pitty. We want environments where we and others can thrive. Were we do NOT have to fight for basic accommodations and understanding. We want environments where we receive understanding and empathy rather than being expected to confirm to the narrow and rigid expectations that are hoisted on us and others. Happy Halloween! Be safe. Enjoy spooky time. Be kind. Because you cant see the need it is easy for people to interpret accomodations as self indulgent or unneccessary. But that couldn’t be further from the truth. It is our job to nurture ourselves and our children. To listen. If we or them do not feel as if we can leave the house, we can honor this and stay home if needed. We also can start thinking about what accomodations can help us to access our normal routine or access an activity we typically cannot. Mobility aids are one type of accomodation an autistic person may need. This could be for physical reasons, such as dyspraxia, struggling with proprioception leading to a lot of accidents/injuries, chronic pain, or severe fatigue, or to accomodate burnout, shutdowns, or heightened anxiety, to name a few. Hope you are all accommodating and being accomodated in the ways you need today 🫶 #actuallyautistic #autism #fyp #latediagnosedautistic #autisticadult #therapistsontiktok #pathologicaldemandavoidance #audhd #mobilityaids

Lateral ableism is when disabled people are ableist to other disabled people. This is one of my biggest pet peeves. When disabled people say they “dont let their disability stop them” in order to invalidate another disabled person thats ableism. Disability is disabling. My disability *does* stop me and prevent me from doing things, as it does for many other disabled people, hence the existence of disability itself. This is something I feel strongly about, not just with my autistic son, but all children.  Autism behaviors can cause parents to fear their own child, I was there. But we started very early on making small changes in what we would accept regardless of his disability. And those small changes turned into 💯 respect! Although i know this doesnt always work, the encouragement from my heart is start early & work hard.  They are capable of change.  #autism #autistic #autisticadult #autismfamily #autismmom

Alt text: Babies born in 2006 at 23-24 weeks in 2006 had a 20% of survival.....im here today a disabled college student and my twin brother is in bootcamp for the Marines Corps  Growing up i moved every 1-2 years, grew up socially isolated, & bullied Im diagnosed with severe Generalized Anxiety Disorder, Social Anxiety Disorder, Major Depressive Disorder, Chronic Suicidal Ideations, Eating Disorder, & PTSD Ive lived through physical, emotional, and sexual abuse & I have attempted on my life & deal with SH I've been Visually Impaired since birth and started using my White Cane🦯 in highschool  I AM AUTISTIC  I live with chronic: pain, fatigue, and headaches Ive lost most of my ability to write and walk functionally....ive had severe mobility and weakness issues in my arms, legs, and hands for a year now Ive recieved Special Education Services since birth & even now, I have accommodations in college Im a member of the LGBTQ Community: Demigirl, Demiromantic, & Omnisexual > my pronouns are SHE/THEY Im an Undergraduate at UW WHITEWATER and majoring in Special Education Im an advocate and love to educate others about Disability, Mental Health, & LGBTQ Community. Finally ready to delve into the FREE studyjng of psychology using proper peer review and cross referencing techniques to help educate myself and connect with others. #fyp #autisticadult #arkansas #alternativegirl #highmaskingautism  YES the term high functioning isnt the best term. High masking is better because you are an individual who is able to highly mask. However this leads to massive internalization which causes long term effects. Also Autism is a spectrum. How I present and experience the world around me varies by day and for sure is different than yours.

Unfortunately 🥺😞 Jasper isn't with us anymore. I tried feeding her and giving her water but she refused. I assumed she was just nervous cuz this was a new environment for her and Mocha is a loud piggy that makes alot of noise especially in the morning. On Thanksgiving Day, she was too weak to walk and I tried force feeding her and giving her water cuz she didn't eat much or drink much water and I knew she needed to at least drink water.  I was going to take her to Petco vet clinic the next day after Thanksgiving since everywhere was closed on Thanksgiving. But an hour before I left to go see my sister at her husband's family house, I noticed she stopped breathing 😔😭.  I don't know if it was my chronic infections I have that spread to her (was told it wasn't contagious tho by my doctors) or if it's something in my environment she was sensitive to or if she was already sick 😷 before I adopted her. But I kinda suspect it's the third situation if anything, cuz Petco and PetSmart 😕 is known to be awful 😞 towards their pets but I didn't realize how truly awful those companies are until yesterday when I read an article about them and the evil they do behind closed doors. I'm heartbroken 💔 even though I only had Jasper for a week. I really 🤔 she was going to last longer than a week!! I 🤔 I was going to at least have her for a year or so. But no. Maybe this is a sign from above, telling me I need to slow down 👇 and grieve the pets I recently lost, people I loved to death, and lose of friendships. Lose of job. Etc.  But instead I rather focus my energy on a pet or my job over dealing with reality and grief. It's been years since some people I love and some animals I loved, passed away. I should be over it by now. But I'm not. I never processed it. I just shoved it away and carried on with my life. Same goes with a bunch of other traumas I been through and continue to go through. I was also constantly told to shut up 😞 and that my emotions didn't matter so that's what I been doing. I just try my hardest to not think about it and move on. Cuz this is life. Life isn't easy and death is part of life. And life isn't always bad. But then u find urself in these moments where u just want to escape it. I used to drink to escape but now it's become owning pets and working alot instead, which I find is much healthier than drinking alcohol and slowly having it kill me. But unfortunately with pets, I get attached and then they die. So that hasn't been easy or helpful.  I love animals wayyyyy too much.  So instead I work alot when I can, to survive and to focus my mind and energy on something else, instead of drowning out my emotions with something harmful like alcohol.  I am becoming a workaholic. I wanted to work yesterday 😕 but I didn't have a way to get there and my support workers couldn't be there for me so I had to sit at home and cry instead. Not great at all. Thankfully I have work today and tomorrow tho. Can't wait 🫸 to go to work and work for a few hours. Just wish I felt more alive today and not 😷 rn. Maybe 🤔 if I have time I can get myself some coffee to wake up and help soothe my throat some.  #cutepetsoftiktok #takingitonedayatatime #grievingjourney #griefandloss #griefsucks😢😢 #griefsupport #restinpeace #animallovers #hamstersoftiktok #petcosucks #petsmartsucks #gonetoosoon💔💔💔 #autisticadult #autisticcreator #audhder #auditoryprocessingdisorder #autismshutdown #drainedasf #drainedmentally #ijustwanttoescape #escape #dissociation #dissociating #sadtiktok #depression #mentalhealthmatters

First few pics is Polly (she's 11 years old and a chocolate retriever, she's my sister husband's family dog). The pics after her is Jersey, she's a golden retriever whose 5 years old and very hyper at times unlike Polly who is very calm and sweet (they are all sweet tbh). Jersey and Polly are my sister husband's family dogs. In the last pic, the smaller golden retriever puppy is Whidbey (my sister puppy she got this year whose now 5.5 months old and growing up so fast! I remember when she was tiny and now she's half the size of Jersey whose 5 years old! She is very hyper and she is hard to train but when I'm around for some reason she listens to me, she sat down 👇 many times I told her to sit, the key is being confident and patient 💞☺️💞 I noticed when it comes to training dogs).  Last week was hard, one of my favorite dogs I helped take care of for 2.5 years and loved for years, was put down which brought up alot of memories of losing other pets and people I loved growing up, especially this year. Buckeyes, one of the old piggies I adopted last year, passed away in October of this year. And on Thanksgiving Day this year, Jasper....passed away 😔 as well 😭. She wasn't doing well at all when I adopted her a week ago but I figured she was just a nervous little hamster 🐹 and would eventually warm up to me.  But no....on Thanksgiving Day, I noticed she didn't want to eat or drink water. She had a very hard time walking around and started seizing in my hands. All the vets were closed that day too so I wasn't able to go back to Petco and take her to the vet. I was hoping she was just going into hibernation or something. But an hour later before I left to see my sister, she died. I just got Jasper.....I was so happy ☺️ to have another hamster 🐹 baby especially since she looked just like Toby and Holly (past hamsters I had who passed away last year). Then to have her just die suddenly 😭 and not being able to say goodbye 🫂 to Oreo, one of my favorite dogs I helped take care of, absolutely destroyed me. And I can't but help to blame myself. I wonder 🤔 if my chronic infections I have spread to her and Buckeyes. But I know Buckeyes was just old. Oreo was really old too. But Jasper? Jasper was only a few months old 😭. This should not have happened. I did everything I was supposed to do.  At least I still have Mocha, my guinea pig and my sister doggy, Whidbey (but maybe 🤔 not for long cuz they are thinking about getting rid of her). At least I still have Polly and Jersey. But I barely get to see them.  Depression been kicking my a$$ alot these days and I'm trying my hardest to stay focused on my future goals for my career with Target 🎯 and trying to survive as much as I can rn. But in reality, I'm so overwhelmed, I feel a mixture of emotions. And feel like I'm coming down 👇 with something as well cuz I been drained, night sweats, muscle cramps, digestive issues, and my throat is bothering me. Cue in dissociating. Which is why I 🤔 I may have passed on one of my chronic infections or an illness I didn't know I had until today. Just thought it was chronic illnesses flaring up. I was told my chronic infections I have are not contagious tho but maybe 🤔 not to humans, but definitely pets. Or maybe 🤔 it was something in my environment or she was sick 😷 prior to me adopting her cuz Petco is known to do that. Just read something terrible 😞 about Petco and PetSmart. Never shopping 🛒 there again.  #autismandholidays #drainedmentally #drainedasf #autismshutdown #auditoryprocessingdisorder #audhder #autisticcreator #autisticadult #recoveringaddict #differentbutnotless #takingitonedayatatime #cutepetsoftiktok #dogsoftiktok

Hyperkeratosis occurs when the skin produces extra layers in response to repeated friction, irritation, or trauma—such as from biting. Over time, the body adapts by thickening the skin in the affected areas, which can result in a callus-like texture. This thickened skin is a common outcome of chronic body-focused repetitive behaviors (BFRBs) like skin biting. While it can reduce the likelihood of pain or sensitivity in the short term, 🔴it may also make the behavior more satisfying due to the increased resistance or texture, reinforcing the habit.🔴 Gentle dermaplaning can be an effective option for reducing thickened skin, especially if done carefully. Dermaplaning involves using a small, precise blade to remove the outermost layer of dead skin cells and fine debris. This method can work well for callus-like thickened skin but requires caution to avoid irritation or accidental injury. #hyperkeratosis #bfrb #autisticadult #skinbiting #dermatophagia

POV: When Someone Thinks They Know More About Your Autism Than You Or The Doctor Who Diagnosed You 🙈🤡🙄🤦🏽‍♀️  Funny thing how people think they know you better than you 😲🙄🤨😤 Many reasons for this - denial, misunderstanding, resistance to change, etc. Just know whatever the reason, none of them are your fault or responsibility.  Your formal diagnosis IS valid. Your self-assessment IS valid. You know what’s not valid? The uneducated opinions of people who have no idea what they’re talking about or interest in learning.   Sometimes change is hard & as I continue to unmask & unpack my journey, I’m just so grateful my diagnosis & treatment, access to accommodations, etc. doesn’t rely on the ignorance of others. My little one hated school for a while because he wanted to be perfect and hated to fail. He has gotten better with failures and I make sure to tell him we have to practice at some things. Meltdowns are extremely stressful for autistic people. During a meltdown or moments of distress, our prefrontal cortex actually shuts down, which causes us to be unable to regulate our emotions or reactions, or manage our harmful impulses. This also causes us to be unable to predict or understand consequences in the moment, and affects our ability to communicate. Meltdowns are emotionally, mentally, cognitively, neurologically, and physically exhausting, and engage the body’s stress responses, which can affect us even days later.  #fyp #foryou #actuallyautistic #autism #autistic #autistiktok #asd #autisticadult #autisticcreator #autismawareness #autismacceptance #autistictiktok #autismeducation #education #meltdown #autisticmeltdown
